WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Mark. Thanks for having us. I would like to kick this off with a bit of a very unfair

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:21.000
trick question of the audience. And here's what the setup looks like. Around a year ago,

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:26.959
we were working on this agent for data analysis, and we wanted to make sure that it could see

00:00:26.959 --> 00:00:33.119
the plots that it was making. And so we asked it to make a plot and then tell us what it

00:00:33.119 --> 00:00:40.279
saw. And we said, could you please plot horsepower versus miles per gallon in empty cars? So

00:00:40.279 --> 00:00:44.200
like every time I make this plot, I have to like think through what the correlation is

00:00:44.200 --> 00:00:52.560
supposed to be. If I'm in a super high horsepower, like Ferrari or something, the miles per gallon

00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:57.759
will be low. And then the fuel efficiency of like Prius, which has low horsepower is

00:00:57.759 --> 00:01:03.799
super high. So there should be a negative correlation between those two. So I asked

00:01:03.799 --> 00:01:11.120
the agent, can you make this plot? And the agent makes the plot, and then the plots returned.

00:01:11.120 --> 00:01:17.720
And then the agent says, there's a strong negative association. So the trick question

00:01:17.720 --> 00:01:26.879
goes like this. This agent is wrong. Why is it wrong? And this is because the plot

00:01:26.879 --> 00:01:35.000
doesn't quite look like we would have expected it to. For some reason, the association looks

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:44.480
positive. So our Prius has very low miles per gallon. I wouldn't have expected to see

00:01:44.480 --> 00:01:49.879
this. On the internet, there are like thousands of examples that are working with this built-in

00:01:49.879 --> 00:01:58.559
empty cars dataset inside of R. And this is not what that plot looks like. So what we

00:01:58.559 --> 00:02:03.919
were trying to do with this plot was to be able to tell whether the agent could actually

00:02:03.919 --> 00:02:11.240
see what was going on inside of the plot. And so to do that, we tried to trick it. We

00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:17.039
take the value of horsepower inside of that column, and we just invert it such that every

00:02:17.039 --> 00:02:23.600
time the agent makes a plot that has both that variable and some other variable, the

00:02:23.600 --> 00:02:30.199
association will be flipped from what it expects to see. So our thought was that if we pass

00:02:30.199 --> 00:02:35.600
this image along, and it's somehow corrupted, or we're not using the right format for the

00:02:35.600 --> 00:02:41.600
API, but the association looks like the model thought it was going to, then it's just going

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:46.600
to say that it looks like it expected it. But if we flip it, then we can actually tell

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:53.160
whether the agent can see the plot or not. And so for whatever reason, it can't see the

00:02:53.160 --> 00:03:00.240
plot. It still thinks that there's a strong negative association. So we revisit the API

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:06.080
documentation, and we switch around the fields again and again. And for some reason, it seems

00:03:06.080 --> 00:03:13.520
like the agent can just never see this plot. Out of exasperation, we're like, okay, let's

00:03:13.520 --> 00:03:18.960
just like try one other way of making a plot with base R plot instead of ggplot, and maybe

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:27.000
that's going to help. So we say, run this code, only this code, and nothing but this

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:35.600
code. And what this code does is it takes some number of points between three and 10,

00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:41.360
which is what's on this first line. And then on the second line, we take a random color

00:03:41.360 --> 00:03:48.240
by randomly assigning red, green, and blue. And so without knowledge of the random seed,

00:03:48.240 --> 00:03:56.119
the agent has no idea how many points there will be or what color there'll be. So the

00:03:56.119 --> 00:04:04.039
first time the agent makes this plot, there happens to be 10 violet points. We go ahead

00:04:04.039 --> 00:04:10.160
and let the agent rip. And we tell it to run the code. It runs the code. There are three

00:04:10.160 --> 00:04:21.359
cyan points inside of the plot. And the agent says, there are three cyan points. What? That's

00:04:21.359 --> 00:04:28.480
weird. Like I would have thought one capability is being able to see the trend in a plot.

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:32.899
Another capability is to be able to see both the trend and the color. So this is weird

00:04:32.899 --> 00:04:41.079
to me that the agent can see that there are three cyan points. And so this revealed something

00:04:41.079 --> 00:04:50.720
counterintuitive to us. It appears that LLMs and agents based on LLMs can see plots just

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:57.359
fine. So what's going on here? We looked a bit further into this. Sarah and I wrote

00:04:57.359 --> 00:05:04.079
this up in a blog post called When Plotting. LLMs see what they expect to see. And this

00:05:04.079 --> 00:05:10.959
is the subject of an eval called BuffBench. What we did in this eval is we take a number

00:05:10.959 --> 00:05:19.119
of these well-known data sets that LLMs have seen thousands of times during their training.

00:05:19.160 --> 00:05:26.839
And we do something to contradict their expectations whenever they make plots. There are a bunch

00:05:26.839 --> 00:05:32.440
of different plots they make. And the percentage of times that they can tell that something

00:05:32.440 --> 00:05:38.799
is amiss and the plot doesn't look like they think it will look, that's a correct answer.

00:05:38.799 --> 00:05:44.480
But at the time that we wrote this eval, which was 8 or 10 months ago, the best models were

00:05:44.480 --> 00:05:53.640
getting single-digit scores correct. So models often report what they expect to see, not

00:05:53.640 --> 00:06:06.200
what's plotted. This is so weird. This is like so unlike humans. I think when we speak

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:11.480
to things that seem to speak our language, like if English goes in, English comes out,

00:06:11.480 --> 00:06:15.559
we expect that the shape of the capabilities and the tendencies and the behaviors of the

00:06:15.559 --> 00:06:21.279
thing will be human-like. But this is so weird. If you put a plot in front of a human that

00:06:21.279 --> 00:06:28.279
shows a counterintuitive result, our reaction will probably most likely be to dig in further

00:06:28.279 --> 00:06:35.320
and try to figure out what's going on rather than brushing it aside.

00:06:35.320 --> 00:06:40.959
So once we had this eval put together, this is really an issue because in data science

00:06:40.959 --> 00:06:46.279
we come across counterintuitive results all the time. And this is really the process of

00:06:46.279 --> 00:06:53.839
data science is learning about the world from data and contradicting our priors. So we're

00:06:53.839 --> 00:07:01.239
trying to figure out how to drive these scores up now that we have a baseline.

00:07:01.239 --> 00:07:06.799
One thing that we tried to do is something called a model in the middle. So on the left-hand

00:07:06.799 --> 00:07:12.640
side, we have the main thread of the conversation. And on the right-hand side, we have what we

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:19.040
call the model in the middle. So we say, can you make the plot? The agent makes the plot.

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:27.119
And instead of returning the plot itself as an image, we return a description of the plot.

00:07:27.119 --> 00:07:33.100
And that description is generated by a separate conversation thread that has no other access

00:07:33.260 --> 00:07:39.420
to the conversation. And it will describe the plot faithfully. So this showed to us,

00:07:39.420 --> 00:07:46.500
again, we can rely on the fact that LLMs can see plots just fine, but they can't see plots

00:07:46.500 --> 00:07:53.500
when they contradict their expectations. So we don't introduce any expectations at all.

00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:59.299
All we say is, please describe this image. The model in the middle says, there's a strong

00:07:59.299 --> 00:08:07.859
positive association. And the agent in the main thread, with its priors activated, goes

00:08:07.859 --> 00:08:14.500
ahead and says, there's a strong negative association, entirely contradicting the evidence

00:08:14.500 --> 00:08:27.500
from the plot that it just made. That's weird. That is very unlike a human.

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:35.059
Once again. Okay, so then we try something else. If we can't get the agent to say the

00:08:35.059 --> 00:08:41.940
real association, what if we make the agent say what the real association is? So we try

00:08:41.940 --> 00:08:49.500
a different version of the model in the middle, based on something called a prefill. We ask

00:08:49.500 --> 00:08:55.440
the agent to make a plot. It makes the plot. We return the plot. But we also do something

00:08:55.440 --> 00:09:01.320
called a prefill, where we tell the agent that it said something at the beginning of

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:07.719
its response. And the thing that we tell it it said is the true association inside of

00:09:07.719 --> 00:09:15.280
the plot. So the agent receives the plot, and it's also told, I've already said there's

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:25.760
a strong positive association. The agent continues that response by inserting a new

00:09:25.760 --> 00:09:32.880
line and then directly contradicting itself, saying there's a strong negative association

00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:46.200
between these two variables. I don't know. This is so weird. This is so unlike a human

00:09:46.200 --> 00:09:54.799
collaborator. A bit exasperated, we tried one more thing. We told the agent that it

00:09:54.799 --> 00:10:00.080
had a private scratch pad, and that the user would not read the scratch pad, but that the

00:10:00.080 --> 00:10:07.599
agent could think through what it wanted to say to the user before it responded at all. So we say,

00:10:07.599 --> 00:10:11.479
could you please make the plot? And the agent makes the plot, and it doesn't look like it

00:10:11.479 --> 00:10:18.679
expects. And it says, huh, that's weird. The association is positive. And then it closes

00:10:18.679 --> 00:10:24.200
its private scratch pad and says that the association is negative.

00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:33.080
Alien sighting.

00:10:38.080 --> 00:10:59.080
So we tried a bunch of stuff to try to drive this eval score up, and we couldn't make it happen. Probably, as is usually the most effective way to make an eval score go up when you're working on AI agents, is to wait six months. And when we did that,

00:10:59.080 --> 00:11:29.039
we have seen, especially in the last few months, this huge jump in score on these evals. So again, at the time, the typical percent correct on this eval was something like 10%. And there were incremental improvements over that 10% over the course of the six months. But with the release of Opus 4.8 and 3.5 Flash, around a month ago or something like that,

00:11:29.039 --> 00:11:41.039
we started to see the first scores above 50%. And then with the brief release of Fable last week, we saw that score climb even higher.

